<p class="">    <h1>Key Challenges in the Intraoperative Neurophysiological Monitoring Device Market</h1>    <ul>        <li><strong>Regulatory Hurdles:</strong> Navigating through stringent regulatory requirements poses a challenge for manufacturers. Compliance with FDA and international standards is time-consuming and can delay product launches.</li>        <li><strong>High Implementation Costs:</strong> The initial investment required for advanced neurophysiological monitoring systems is steep, which may deter smaller hospitals and surgical centers from adopting these technologies.</li>        <li><strong>Shortage of Skilled Professionals:</strong> The lack of trained personnel to operate and interpret the data from monitoring devices limits the widespread use and effectiveness of these technologies in surgical settings.</li>        <li><strong>Integration with Existing Systems:</strong> Incompatibility with existing surgical systems and electronic health records can hinder the adoption of new intraoperative monitoring devices, leading to inefficiencies and increased costs.</li>        <li><strong>Technological Complexity:</strong> The intricate nature of neurophysiological monitoring can result in operational challenges, including longer training times and potential frustration for surgical teams unfamiliar with advanced technologies.</li>    </ul>    <h2>Potential Growth Opportunities in the Intraoperative Neurophysiological Monitoring Device Market</h1>    <ul>        <li><strong>Increasing Surgical Procedures:</strong> The rise in complex surgical procedures, especially in neurosurgery and orthopedic surgeries, is expected to drive the demand for intraoperative monitoring devices.</li>        <li><strong>Technological Advancements:</strong> Innovations such as wireless monitoring devices and AI-driven analytics can enhance the efficacy and usability of neurophysiological monitoring, presenting significant growth opportunities for manufacturers.</li>        <l